<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>This was after cops received a tip-off about fake goods being taken from KZN to Gauteng. Sedibe said their team responded, spotted and stopped three vehicles fitting the description given. He said during the search, police found vehicles loaded with illegal goods, clothing and takkies.The five were arrested on the spot.Meanwhile, a passerby found another load of illegal goods abandoned in the bush not far from the Lebombo border post and called the cops. The police found the loot wrapped in black refuse bags. They contained fake branded takkies. The combined street value of the loot is estimated to be over R3 million.Mpumalanga police commissioner Lieutenant-General Mondli Zuma praised residents for informing the police about the illegal goods and reporting the suspects to the police.Zuma said it showed community involvement and selflessness by the people involved.